[Student "S"]
{North is to play 3NT. East leads the \HQ.

Winners:   \S=1  \H=2  \D=1  \C=3  Total = 7

You need two more winners and \Ds is your longest combined suit. But you can only establish one extra winner in \Ds, and before you could even do that the defenders would have taken a bunch of \H tricks.

So you must turn to the \Ss for the extra two winners.

You win the first \H and lead . . . which \S? If you play the \SQ you will go down, even if East has the \SK. He would cover and you would be held to just 2 \S tricks.

The only way to get 3 tricks from this holding is to play West for the \SK. So play a \S to dummy's \SA and then a small \S back toward your \S Q J. Here West puts the \SK on and you are home-free.

You were a little lucky that West's \SK fell on the second round. 

If it had not dropped you would just have played a third round of \Ss, hoping for a 3-3 split in the suit.

Clickagain. 

You could also have gotten 3 \S winners with this distribution.}
[Play "W"]HQ

